The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, Feb. 13: Sebi has restrained Shankar Sharma of First Global Stock Broking (FGSB) from buying, selling or dealing in securities and from associating in securities market in any manner for one year. The order follows investigations launched by Sebi in early 2001 into transactions done by FGSB in 10 securities.                             
	 Mumbai, Feb. 13: The Reserve Bank of India has relaxed the provision for opening of dollar account used by diamond exporters for importing the rough precious stone. The RBI has delegated powers of opening such accounts to permitted authorised dealers.                             
	 New Delhi, Feb. 13: The Telecom Regulatory Authority of India (Trai) said no separate category of licence or registration was required for value-added services. The telecom regulator said there was need for uniformity in various licences to pave way for the growth of such services.                            
	 New Delhi, Feb. 13: Liquor baron Vijay Mallya is willing to offer more than 15 per cent stake in United Spirits Ltd (USL) to Diageo and will not oppose if the London-based firm seeks board representation.                             
	 New Delhi, Feb. 13: Banks have started providing more credit in the last few weeks, Planning Commission deputy chairman Montek Singh Ahluwalia said.                            
	 New Delhi, Feb. 13: The government has given initial approval to 10 out of the 40 applicants seeking permission to set up mega food parks, food processing secretary Ashok Sinha said. Those selected will be given the grant in phases according to their course of action, he said.                            
	 New Delhi, Feb. 13: The cabinet is likely to decide next week on giving a three-year drilling holiday or moratorium on firms such as ONGC and Reliance Industries, which are facing problems in sourcing drilling rigs because of the global scarcity.                                                                                                                           
